What hath all my knowledge of natures secrets gained me ? Onely this, the losse of a better knowledge, the losse of divine studies, which makes the immortaU part of man his soule blessed. I have found, that my knowledge has beene. a heavy burden, and has kept downe my good thoughts but I will remove the cause, which are these bookes which I doe purpose here before you all to burne. They all intreated him to spare the bookes, because in them there were those things that after-ages might receive great benefit by. He would not hearken unto them, but threw them all into the fire, and in that flame burnt the greatest learning in the world. Then did he dispose of aH his goods some part he gave to poor schollers, and some he gave to other poore folkes nothing left he for him selfe then caused he to be made in the church-waU a cell, where he locked himselfe in, and there remained tiU his death. His time hee spent in prayer, medita tion, and such divine exercises, and did seeke by aU

ocr.region: 290 CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE. XXXV Cette crise fut plus longue que ceile qui avait prcd, et il y eut un moment o le mdecin dsespra du succs. Ce n'tait plus l'action du poison qui tait  craindre, mais l'ef-fet de cette secousse morale sur une organisation dj pro-fondment atteinte. Ludovic s'accusait et se dsesprait, il rejetait sur lui la responsabilit de cette rechute, et parlait de suivre la jeune fille si elle n'en rchappait pas. Il demandait pardon au doc-teur de n'avoir pas mieux suivi ses conseils et offrait de quitter la chambre afin de ne pas compromettre de nouveau les effets de son traitement. Mais celui-ci avait rflchi, et cette fois son avis fut tout oppos. - Non, lui dit-il, restez. - Mais si je commets encore quelque imprudence ? - Restez, vous dis-je, le mal est fait. Vtre prsence a amen une crise, votre absence en amnerait une auire, plus fcheuse encore. Je ne connaissais pas cette enfant c'est une tte de fer. Il faut que vous soyez l, quand elle reprendra ses sens. Restez. - J'obis alors. - Et que le ciel vous inspire, Ludovic, quand le moment sera venu. Cette jeune fille a au coeur une plaie dont je ne puis la gurir et que la Facult en corps ne gurirait pas c'est le dgot de la vie. Tchez d'en venir  bout et j'incli-nerai ma science devant la vtre. L'aimez-vous ? - Si je l'aime 1 Vous me demandez si je l'aime! Ne le voyez-vous pas ? - Eh bien 1 alors, il y a quelque chance pour que vous russissiez. Mais, ou je me trompe fort, ou ce sera une cure difficile. ocr.region: OF FRIER RUSH. 295 whereat his master had great marvade then they sate downe to breakfast, which being ended they went home, and did such thinges as were there to bee done when his dame sawe that he had so soone ended his busines, she thought that he was a profitable servant, and said Httle but let him alone. Then it fortuned upon a day the Priour and his brethren were assembled together in a generaU counsaile, and as they stood talking together, the Priour remembered Rush, and anon he said unto his brethren Friends we have here Rush which is our maister Cooke in our kitchin, and be is an olde servant, and much diligent and true service he hath done to us, and he hath continued among us longer then any servant that ever wee had wherefore me thinke it reason, that hee were promoted into some other office, and made a brother among us. Then all the whole Covent with one voice said they were content it should so be. So the Priour sent for Rush, and when he was come before him and aU bis brethren, the Priour said, Rush it is so, thou hast beene here a long season, and we have found thee hitherto a true and diligent servant, wherefore wee wdl that thou be promoted, and take upon thee an habite as we have, and to become a brother among us. Rush answered and said my Maisters I thanke you aU, and then the Priour gave Rush an habite, and put it on his backe, and so Rush became a brother in the place, neverthelesse he kept his office stiU. How Frier Rush made Truncheons for the Friers to fight withaU. When Rush had on the habite of a Frier, and was a brother in the place, he had more vacation dayes

prediction.sentence: How Friar Rush made Truncheons for the Friars to Fight With All.
prediction.region: Of Friar Rush. In the space of seven years, Friar Rush had served well, earning the love and favor of all those around him. One day, the Prior and his brethren were gathered for a council, and the Prior spoke of Rush, the master cook in their kitchen, who had been a faithful and diligent servant. He suggested that Rush be promoted to a higher office and made a brother among them. The entire convent agreed, and Rush was called before them. The Prior informed Rush of his promotion, offering him the habit of a Friar, and Rush accepted with gratitude. However, he continued to serve as the master cook. Later, Rush made truncheons for his fellow Friars to fight with during his free time.

ocr.sentence: CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE.
ocr.region: CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE. 251 comme une exception parmi le commun des hommes, et que vous tiez ce qu'ils sont tous, perfides et trompeurs  l'occasion. Quand je relevai la tte, l'obscurit la plus complte salait faite dans votre logement, et une lueur d'espoir tra-, versa mon esprit. Point de doute vous alliez venir, vous alliez paratre. Nulle puissance humaine ne m'et contrainte  croire que vous passeriez la journe sans me voir et sans tenir la promesse que vous m'aviez faite. Vous tiez-donc en. chemin j'en tais convaincue comme d'un article de foi. En - effet, la sonnette retentit quelqu'un tait l. - Ab 1 enfin, m'criai-je, le voici Dieu soit lou ! Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous? A quel titre se prsentait-il 1 Etait-ce de votre part? Que pouvait-il avoir  me dire? A -tout. prendre, si c'tait votre messager, vous aviez eu, en le choisissant, la main singulirement malheureuse. Il faut que ma physionomie ait exprim, en partie du moins, les sentiments qui m'agitaient, ou bien que Melchior et prpar, en habile acteur, les nuances de son rle. Tou-jours est-il qu'il s'en tira  son avantage et se conduisit de manire  me dsarmer. Dans l'opinion que je m'en tais forme, cet homme devait porter en tout lieu et en toute cir-constance les airs impertinents qui lui taient habituels et dont j'avais eu tant  souffrir. Je me figurais qu'il allait le prendre sur le mme pied et se mettre  l'aise chez moi comme il s'y

prediction.region: 'agitaient, car Melchior parut troubl ds qu'il me vit. Il balbutia quelques excuses pour votre absence et me tendit une lettre que vous lui aviez charg de me remettre. Je la pris sans un mot, mes yeux toujours fixs sur lui avec une froideur glaciale. Melchior comprit qu'il tait temps pour lui de partir et, aprs une dernire salutation maladroite, il se retira. Je refermai la porte et me dirigeai vers mon fauteuil, o je m'assis lentement en gardant la lettre bien en vue. Je ne savais pas si j'allais la lire tout de suite ou la dchirer sans mme l'ouvrir. Finalement, je dcidai de la lire, plus pour satisfaire ma curiosit que pour dcouvrir des nouvelles que je pouvais aisment deviner. Et ce que j'y lus ne fit que confirmer mes pires craintes.

Nulle puissance humaine ne m'et contrainte  croire que vous passeriez la journe sans me voir et sans tenir la promesse que vous m'aviez faite. Vous tiez-donc en. chemin j'en tais convaincue comme d'un article de foi. En - effet, la sonnette retentit quelqu'un tait l. - Ab 1 enfin, m'criai-je, le voici Dieu soit lou ! Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous? A quel titre se prsentait-il 1 Etait-ce de votre part? Que pouvait-il avoir  me dire? A -tout. prendre, si c'tait votre messager, vous aviez eu, en le choisissant, la main singulirement malheureuse. Il faut que ma physionomie ait exprim, en partie du moins, les sentiments qui m'agitaient, ou bien que Melchior et prpar, en habile acteur, les nuances de son rle. Tou-jours est-il qu'il s'en tira  son avantage et se conduisit de manire  me dsarmer. Dans l'opinion que je m'en tais forme, cet homme devait porter en tout lieu et en toute cir-constance les airs impertinents qui lui taient habituels et dont j'avais eu tant  souffrir. Je me figurais qu'il allait le prendre sur le mme pied et se mettre  l'aise chez moi comme il s'y

prediction.region: 'agitaient, car Melchior parut troubl ds qu'il me vit. Il balbutia quelques excuses pour votre absence et me tendit une lettre que vous lui aviez charg de me remettre. Je la pris sans un mot, mes yeux toujours fixs sur lui avec une froideur glaciale. Melchior comprit qu'il tait temps pour lui de partir et, aprs une dernire salutation maladroite, il se retira. Je refermai la porte et me dirigeai vers mon fauteuil, o je m'assis lentement en gardant la lettre bien en vue. Je ne savais pas si j'allais la lire tout de suite ou la dchirer sans mme l'ouvrir. Finalement, je dcidai de la lire, plus pour satisfaire ma curiosit que pour dcouvrir des nouvelles que je pouvais aisment deviner. Et ce que j'y lus ne fit que confirmer mes pires craintes.

Quand je relevai la tte, l'obscurit la plus complte salait faite dans votre logement, et une lueur d'espoir tra-, versa mon esprit. Point de doute vous alliez venir, vous alliez paratre. Nulle puissance humaine ne m'et contrainte  croire que vous passeriez la journe sans me voir et sans tenir la promesse que vous m'aviez faite. Vous tiez-donc en. chemin j'en tais convaincue comme d'un article de foi. En - effet, la sonnette retentit quelqu'un tait l. - Ab 1 enfin, m'criai-je, le voici Dieu soit lou ! Je courus vers la porte et ouvris. C'tait Melchior. XXVI Je ne chercherai pas, Ludovic,  vous raconter ce que j'prouvai  la vue de cet homme. Ce fut un sentiment si bizarre, si ml, si excessif qu'il me serait impossible de l'analyser. Ce qui y dominait, c'tait la colre vis--vis de vous, et vis--vis de lui de la rpugnance. Pourquoi tait-il l et non pas vous? A quel titre se prsentait-il 1 Etait-ce de votre part? Que pouvait-il avoir  me dire? A -tout. prendre, si c'tait votre messager, vous aviez eu, en le choisissant, la main singulirement malheureuse. Il faut que ma physionomie ait exprim, en partie du moins, les sentiments qui m'agitaient, ou bien que Melchior et prpar, en habile acteur, les nuances de son rle. Tou-jours est-il qu'il s'en tira  son avantage et se conduisit de manire  me dsarmer. Dans l'opinion que je m'en tais forme, cet homme devait porter en tout lieu et en toute cir-constance les airs impertinents qui lui taient habituels et dont j'avais eu tant  souffrir. Je me figurais qu'il allait le prendre sur le mme pied et se mettre  l'aise chez moi comme il s'y

ocr.region: CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE. 283 quer leur destination. C'taient des souvenirs laisss  des amies d'enfance ou des dons  de pauvres gens du voisinage qu'elle avait coutume de secourir. Dans l'acte qui instituait le jeune avocat pour son hritier, ces divers voeux taient exprims dans la forme la plus simple et la plus touchante. Elle s'excusait d'avoir si peu  offrir, et priait qu'on lui tint compte de l'intention saps s'arrter  la valeur des choses. Chaque legs tait d'ailleurs appropri  la personne avec un soin dlicat qui y ajoutait un nouveau prix. Marguerite eut une dernire attention elle laissa son se-crtaire ouvert et plaa sur la tablette la pice qui rendait Ludovic matre de tout rgler chez elle et d'agir  son gr. Prs du testament tait l'anneau, ce triste et mystrieux em-blme. Ds le premier abord les yeux devaient se porter sur ces objets, et le jeune homme y reconnatrait quelles avaient t, au moment de quitter ce monde, la pense de la mou-rante et sa proccupation. Quand elle en eut fini avec la terre, Marguerite songea au ciel elle s'agenouilla devant le portrait de sa grand'mre et pria avec ferveur. Que fut cette prire? Sans doute un acte de contritipp et en mme temps un cri de dsespoir. Elle prit Dieu  tmoin, et, lui montrant l'tat de son me, invo-qua sa misricorde ayec un accent plor. Puis s'adressant  cette aeule qui avait si saintement vcu et si saintement fini,  sa mre moissonne avant le temps et qui, son mari mort, avait, elle aussi, manqu de courage, elle les conjura sans doute d'intercder pour elle et d'obtenir qu'elle ft admise  leurs cts, daps le sjour des mes pures ou purifies par le repentir. Elle leur demanda d'unir leurs prires  la sienne afin d'en augmenter l'effet et d'ob-tenir ce pardon qui descend d'en haut sur les coeurs humi-lis et sincres. Quand elle eut mis sa conscience en paix, autant que le permettait l'acte violent auquel elle tait rsolue, elle monta sur son lit, ajusta ses vtements de manire  ce que rien n'y pt amener du dsordre, s'tendit sur les coussins, et, s'emparant d'une petite fiole qui tait  sa porte, elle l'ap-procha de ses lvres. 1 Quelques minutes aprs , elle tait plonge dans un en-gourdissement profond.

247 of Fryer Bacon told the other young man that his father had received it wrongly. He answered again that it was fair. At last, there were such foul words between them, and their tempers were so heated, that they stabbed each other with their daggers and fell down dead. Fryer Bacon, seeing them fall, ran to them, but it was too late; they were breathless by the time he arrived. This made him grieve exceedingly. He judged that they had received the cause of their deaths through the glass. He took the glass in his hand and uttered words to this effect: 'Wretched Bacon! Wretched in thy knowledge, in thy understanding, wretched for thy art hath been the ruin of these two gentlemen. Had I been busy with the holy things that my order ties me to, I would not have had the time that made this wicked glass - wicked I well may call it - that is the cause of so vile an act. Would it were sensible! Then it should feel my wrath. But being as it is, I ruin it for ruining them.' And with that, he broke his rare and wonderful glass, the likes of which the whole world had not seen. 

In this grief, he received news of the deaths of Vandermast and Fryer Bungey, which increased his grief and made him sorrowful. For three days, he would not eat anything but kept his chamber.

247 of Fryer Bacon told the other young man that his father had received it wrongly. He answered again that it was fair. At last, there were such foul words between them, and their tempers were so heated, that they stabbed each other with their daggers and fell down dead. Fryer Bacon, seeing them fall, ran to them, but it was too late; they were breathless by the time he arrived. This made him grieve exceedingly. He judged that they had received the cause of their deaths through the glass. He took the glass in his hand and uttered words to this effect: 'Wretched Bacon! Wretched in thy knowledge, in thy understanding, wretched for thy art hath been the ruin of these two gentlemen. Had I been busy with the holy things that my order ties me to, I would not have had the time that made this wicked glass - wicked I well may call it - that is the cause of so vile an act. Would it were sensible! Then it should feel my wrath. But being as it is, I ruin it for ruining them.' And with that, he broke his rare and wonderful glass, the likes of which the whole world had not seen. 

In this grief, he received news of the deaths of Vandermast and Fryer Bungey, which increased his grief and made him sorrowful. For three days, he would not eat anything but kept his chamber.

ocr.region: CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE. 269 o cette scne se passait. Par le concours des circonstances, j'tais compromise  un point qu'aucune rparation n'tait possible, si ce n'est celle que pouvait m'offrir Melcbior. Son but tait atteint il m'avait mise  la discrtion de son hon-neur. Triste garantie ! et je le vis bien plus tard. Je succombai une barrire s'leva entre vous et moi je ne pouvais plus tre  vous, Ludovic. Les heures s'cou-laient il fallut prendre un parti. Encore quelques instants, et vous alliez venir chercher votre fiance impossible de vous attendre en vous voyant je serais tombe morte  vos pieds. Nous primes donc, Melchior et moi, nos dernires dis-positions. Au petit jour, et quand la porte fut ouverte, il quitta la maison. Un rendez-vous avait t fix, et je devais aller le rejoindre. Il passa sans tre aperu peut-tre le concierge tait-il son complice. Quant  moi, je restai pendant une heure encore abme dans mes regrets et mes remords. -Toutes vos bonts me revinrent alors  la mmoire, et je me trouvai bien ingrate, bien cruelle et en mme temps bien dchue. -Qu'ai liez-vous penser de moi? Hlas 1 quoi que vous pussiez en penser, la ralit dpasserait vos suppositions. J'tais une fille dshonore ! XXX - Pourtant, Ludovic, je vous crivis quelques mots, non pas tels que j'aurais voulu les crire, mais assez prcis pour que dsormais vous me regardassiez comme perdue pour vous. Puis j'enlevai de mon doigt l'anneau qui me venait de ma grand'mre et qui avait si mal prserv mon honneur. Je n'tais plus digne de le porter, quoi qu'il arrivt et de quel-que faon que tournassent les choses. Je rejoignis Melchior et le trouvai ivre de son bonheur. Moi-mme,  ce premier moment, j'prouvai ce vertige des sens qui n'est que la fausse monnaie de l'amour. Melchior

Le premier coup de cette loi dsorganisatrice a t ressenti  Reims le 24 novembre suivant lorsque le conseil gnral du dpartement de la Marne a interdit au chapitre de l'glise mtropolitaine de continuer l'office public. Le chapitre a dclar ne pas pouvoir obtemprer car la plupart des prires qu'il faisait taient des fondations, une dette sacre qu'il devait payer chaque jour. Mgr l'archevque a t inform de la rponse du chapitre.

ocr.region: LES TLPHONISTES DANS LA BATAILLE 9 III LA FERME DE BEAUSJOUR L A feuille  la main, le sergent, debout devant l'abri du colonel, faisait la rpartition des postes. - Duruy, dit-il, tu vas monter avec tes hommes au secteur I, tu longeras un peu la route jusqu'aux boyaux B 1 et B 2, au tournant du ruisseau, ils sont perpendiculaires  la Grande Transversale, aprs quoi tu monteras tout droit jus-qu'au poste du commandant. Ne t'amuse pas en chemin, car  peu prs cinq cents mtres avant d'arriver, il voltige des bom-bes!. Legrand, tu prends le secteur H, dangereux pour les marmites, surtout au Bois Equerre tu suivras le boyau central jusqu'au boyau Boscary, o tu trouveras le poste de son com-mandant. Attention vous autres, baissez la tte, les balles tra-versent la route! Je garde deux hommes avec moi au poste du colonel,  da borne 16. La nuit tait venne, pas de lune, une obscurit complte rgnait sur les tranches, et sauf les coups de fusils espacs, partant des premires lignes, la soire tait calme. Les fuses dans le ciel irradiaient par moments l'horizon de leur courbe gracieuse, inondant les parapets d'une lueur blafarde. L'quipe se spara en deux. Puis,  la file, les nouveaux venus longrent la route le plus prs possible du remblai pour viter les balles perdues qui froufroutaient avec un bruit de soie, allant frapper les troncs d'arbres de l'autre ct du ruis-seau. - Pour une belle nuit, c'est une beMe nuit, remarqua R-gnier, un combat de ngres sous un tunnel et  chaque fuse il gouaillait Ah! la belle bleue! - Allez, activez le mouvement, lana Legrand impatient, en laissant derrire lui Duruy qui entrait dans son boyau, nous avons encore un bout de chemin! Sans se dtourner il poursuivit sa marche  ttons, cher-chant  ehaque trou la pancarte indicatrice.

Ne t'amuse pas en chemin, car  peu prs cinq cents mtres avant d'arriver, il voltige des bom-bes!. Legrand, tu prends le secteur H, dangereux pour les marmites, surtout au Bois Equerre tu suivras le boyau central jusqu'au boyau Boscary, o tu trouveras le poste de son com-mandant. Attention vous autres, baissez la tte, les balles tra-versent la route! Je garde deux hommes avec moi au poste du colonel,  da borne 16. La nuit tait venne, pas de lune, une obscurit complte rgnait sur les tranches, et sauf les coups de fusils espacs, partant des premires lignes, la soire tait calme. Les fuses dans le ciel irradiaient par moments l'horizon de leur courbe gracieuse, inondant les parapets d'une lueur blafarde. L'quipe se spara en deux. Puis,  la file, les nouveaux venus longrent la route le plus prs possible du remblai pour viter les balles perdues qui froufroutaient avec un bruit de soie, allant frapper les troncs d'arbres de l'autre ct du ruis-seau. - Pour une belle nuit, c'est une beMe nuit, remarqua R-gnier, un combat de ngres sous un tunnel et  chaque fuse il gouaillait Ah! la belle bleue! - Allez, activez le mouvement, lana Legrand impatient, en laissant derrire lui Duruy qui entrait dans son boyau, nous avons encore un bout de chemin! Sans se dtourner il poursuivit sa marche  ttons, cher-chant  ehaque trou la pancarte indicatrice.

ocr.sentence: CE PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE.
ocr.region: CE qu'on PEUT VOIR DANS UNE rue. 257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. Il faut si. peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui ! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, -on puise des mo-tifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant- de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis la confiance me manqua. Il n'y eut l-dedans ni raisonnement, ni calcul mais une force imprieuse et presque indpen-dante de ma volont. Puis je me payais de dfaites. Pourquoi troubler votre scurit et veiller vos soupons? La chose en valait-elle la peine? Cet homme, en venant chez moi, avait obi  un caprice probablement il n'y reviendrait plus. Et s'il revenait, quoi de plus ais que de le remettre  sa place et de faire justice de ses airs cavaliers ? tait-il besoin d'aide pour cela et ne valait-il pas mieux procder sans bruit, sans clat, .comme une femme peut et doit le faire, que de mettre deux hommes en prsence et jusqu'aux prises pour un si lger motif? Voil  quelles impressions je cdai sans m'en rendre bien compte, ni pntrer trop avant dans mon coeur Peut-tre, hlas ! en interrogeant mieux ce coeur, aurais-je trouv le dernier mot de ces rticences. La suite ne l'a que trop prouv j'tais dj touche, j'entrais dans cette srie de faiblesses qui m'ont perdue. C'est ici que j'ai besoin de votre pardon, Ludovic, d'un pardon absolu et gnreux. Point d'excuse possible, rien qui puisse pallier ce commen-cement de trahison. Vous aviez t pour moi le meilleur, le plus dvou et le plus fidle des amis vous n'aviez qu'une pense, mon bonheur qu'un but, notre union. Jamais, c'est une justice que je me plais  vous rendre, aucun chagrin ne m'est venu de vous si j'exprimais un dsir, vous vous em-pressiez de le satisfaire si j'avais un ennui, vous vous offriez - le partager. Vous tiez de ces loyaux compagnons qu'une femme est trop heureuse de rencontrer dans sa vie, qui l'as-sistent dans les bons et les mauvais jours et se donnent sans rserve comme sans calcul. Je voyais tout cela, je le sentais et ne mconnaissais point-vos mrites. Lui, au contraire, qu'tait-il et quel fonds pouvais-je -

Sans s'en douter, douard avait fait le tour du parc au lieu d'aller tout droit par l'alle du milieu, il avait tourn sur lui-mme et tait revenu  son point de dpart. C'tait bien l la porte du jardin. Il n'tait que neuf heures. La cloche continuait  sonner. Sans doute on s'tait aperu de son absence. Ce second coup de cloche tait pour l'appeler. Encore un effort et ses ennemis vont s'arrter, bien sr il n'oseront pas le poursuivre si prs de la maison. En tout cas, il y arrivera le premier! Le petit douard se trompait. La poursuite continuait. Mais douard tait rentr dans le jardin. Toute sa famille tait l qui l'appelait, qui le cherchait. Son pre tait sur la plate-forme du perron. Les domestiques effars couraient partout avec des lanternes. Chacun criait douard, douard ! La voix de sa soeur venait jusqu' lui. Papa ! papa ! s'cria douard, cher papa! je suis l ! Et le petit douard tombait  moiti mort de peur dans les bras de son pre. Mais il n'arrivait pas seul. Les voleurs, les gendarmes, tous ses ennemis, tous ses perscuteurs, anims sans doute, eux aussi, par leur course, avaient franchi la porte du jardin et faisaient effrontment irruption dans le salon en sonnant une fanfare clatante. Mais douard tait rentr dans le jardin. Toute sa famille tait l qui l'appelait, qui le cherchait. Son pre tait sur la plate-forme du perron. So soon as they heard him play, against their wills, they fell a-dancing, and that after such a laborious manner that they quickly wearied themselves, for they had all the while the bags of money in their hands. Yet had Fryer Bacon not revenge enough of them, but bid his man Miles leave them some larger measure as he thought fitting, which Miles did. Miles straight led them out of the house into the fields. They followed him, dancing after a wild and antic manner. Then led he them over a broad dike full of water, and they followed him still, but not so good a way as he went, for he went over the bridge, but they by reason of their dancing could not keep the bridge but fell off and danced through the water. Then led he them through a way where a horse might very well have been up to the belly, they followed him, and were so dirty as though they had wallowed in the mire like swine. Sometimes he gave them rest, only to laugh at them. Then they were so sleepy when he did not play that they fell to the ground. Then on a sudden, he would play again and make them start up and follow him. Thus kept he them the better part of the night.

ocr.sentence: he said to Rush, thou lewd fellow, what hast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ?
ocr.region: 277 OF FRIER RUSH. then he said to Rush, thou lew d fellow, what bast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ? Rush answered and said sir, I have done nothing but as you commanded me. That is not, said the Priour, for I commaunded thee to take greace and grease but the wheeles and the axeltrees, and thou hast taken tarre and annointed it all over, both within and without. Why hast thou done so ? Sir said Rush, I understoode you bad me doe so. And when the Priour sawe there was no other remedie, he commanded his servants to makeready another waggon, and in the meane season, the Priour went into his chamber, and put on another babite, and came againe and mounted into the waggon and went their way, and so long they rode, that they came to their iourneyes end. And when they were alighted at their lodging, the Priour caUed for his supper, and anon every thing was made ready, and the good man of the house and the Priour sate downe to supper together, and made good cheere and then the Priour called for wine of the best, and anon he had his commandement. And when the good man of the house and the Priour had supped, Rush and bis fellowes sate downe to the rever sions that their maisters bad left, but they had no wine wherefore Rush was very sad, and ever he mused by what policie he might get some wine. And anon he called the wife of the house and said Mistresse, I pray you fill a pottle of wine for me and my fellowes, and so shee did and when that was gone, they caUed for another and then they called for the third, and so ended their

prediction.sentence: He said to Rush, 'Thou lewd fellow, what have you done to this wagon that I am dressed up in?'
prediction.region: 277 of friar Rush. Then he said to Rush, 'Thou lewd fellow, what have you done to this wagon that I am thus arrayed therein?' Rush answered and said, 'Sir, I have done nothing but as you commanded me.' 'That is not,' said the Prior, 'for I commanded you to take grease and grease the wheels and the axles, and you have taken tar and anointed it all over, both within and without. Why have you done so?' 'Sir,' said Rush, 'I understood you bad me do so.' And when the Prior saw there was no other remedy, he commanded his servants to make ready another wagon. In the meantime, the Prior went into his chamber, put on another habit, and came again and mounted into the wagon and went their way. They rode so long that they came to their journey's end. And when they alighted at their lodging, the Prior called for his supper, and immediately everything was made ready. The good man of the house and the Prior sat down to supper together, made good cheer, and then the Prior called for wine of the best, and immediately he was served. When the good man of the house and the Prior had supped, Rush and his fellows sat down to the provisions that their masters had left, but they had no wine. Therefore, Rush was very sad and mused by what policy he might get some wine. And he called the wife of the house and said, 'Mistress, I pray you fill a pottle of wine for me and my fellows,' and so she did. When that was gone, they called for another, and then they called for the third, and so they ended their meal.

ocr.region: 274 A PLEASANT HISTORIE had been there should have seene good buffets given on both parties. And when Frier Rush saw that they were fighting together, anon he blew out all the candles and lamps that were burning in the church, and left no manner of Hght therein whereby the one might see the other and when he had so done, be tooke his truncheon in his hand, and went into the Quier among the thickest of the Friers the which were fighting freshly without light, and there he laid so lustily about, that many of them he felled to the ground, and left them there for dead, and when he had so done, he stole his way from them, and as hee went, he found standing in the portaU of the Quier, a great olde deske, and anon hee tooke the deske betweene both his hands, and threw it over the portad into the Quier among aU the Friers, and hurt many sore, in so much that some had an arme broken, and some a legge, and other some had their noses, cleane pared from their faces, that the bloud ranne in their mouthes, and as for broken heads to the hard scalpe were no dainty, for every man had one, there scaped none free away, who had been there, should have had a goodly pastime to see the Friers creepe about the Quier, and in steede of Domine labia they cried out alas and well away. Then when the fray was done, and all the noyse seased, Rush came in among them with a candell light in his hand, and made as he had knowne nothing thereof, and said to them Fie for shame sirs, how fortuned this discord to faU among your selves ? I see well now you regard not your honour, nor the good

And when Frier Rush saw that they were fighting together, anon he blew out all the candles and lamps that were burning in the church, and left no manner of fight therein whereby the one might see the other and when he had so done, he tooke his truncheon in his hand, and went into the Quier among the thickest of the Friers the which were fighting freshly without light, and there he laid so lustily about, that many of them he felled to the ground, and left them there for dead, and when he had so done, he stole his way from them, and as hee went, he found standing in the portall of the Quier, a great olde deske, and anon hee tooke the deske betweene both his hands, and threw it over the portall into the Quier among all the Friers, and hurt many sore, in so much that some had an arme broken, and some a legge, and other some had their noses, cleane pared from their faces, that the bloud ranne in their mouthes, and as for broken heads to the hard scalpe were no dainty, for every man had one, there scaped none free away, who had been there, should have had a goodly pastime to see the Friers creepe about the Quier, and in steede of Domine labia they cried out alas and well away. Then when the fray was done, and all the noyse seased, Rush came in among them with a candell light in his hand, and made as he had knowne nothing thereof, and said to them Fie for shame sirs, how fortuned this discord to fall among your selves ? I see well now you regard not your honour, nor the good

How Friar Rush grimed the wagon with tar, and what cheer he made in the country. Another time it happened that the Prior had a journey to ride into the country for a little business that he had there to do, and immediately he called Rush, his servant, to him and said, "Rush, go your way into the court and take with you a dish full of grease, and grease well the wheels and axletrees of the wagon and make all things ready against tomorrow in the morning, for I must ride forth tomorrow betimes." Then Rush departed from his master and went about his business. Instead of grease, he took a great vessel full of tar and anointed the wagon all over with it, both within and without, and especially in the place where the Prior should sit. When he had done, he returned to his master's chamber. The Prior then demanded of Rush if he had done as he commanded him. "Yes, sir," said Rush, "you may ride when it pleases you," and so they went to their beds. On the morrow, the Prior and Rush, his servant, with their other company, rose up very early in the morning to accomplish their journey. They went to their wagon, and when the Prior had entered it, he perceived himself all betrayed and smeared, and all his clothes were filed therewith.

Hence, for I shall cause them to be damned, and I shall bring their bodies and souls into the burning fire of hell, there to remain world without end, and of me shall be spoken a thousand years hereafter. How Friar Rush grimed the wagon with tar, and what cheer he made in the country. Another time it happened that the Prior had a journey to ride into the country for a little business that he had there to do, and immediately he called Rush, his servant, to him and said, "Rush, go your way into the court and take with you a dish full of grease, and grease well the wheels and axletrees of the wagon and make all things ready against tomorrow in the morning, for I must ride forth tomorrow betimes." Then Rush departed from his master and went about his business. Instead of grease, he took a great vessel full of tar and anointed the wagon all over with it, both within and without, and especially in the place where the Prior should sit. When he had done, he returned to his master's chamber. The Prior then demanded of Rush if he had done as he commanded him. "Yes, sir," said Rush, "you may ride when it pleases you," and so they went to their beds. On the morrow, the Prior and Rush, his servant, with their other company, rose up very early in the morning to accomplish their journey. They went to their wagon, and when the Prior had entered it, he perceived himself all betrayed and smeared, and all his clothes were filed therewith.

ocr.region: OF FRIER RUSH. 273 filling their malicious mindes and angry hearts, every man after other went privately to Frier Rush to lend them staves, in so much that there was not a Frier in the place but he had one, and they never went without their staves under their habite, and the one knew not that the other had any, they kept them so secretly. And when Frier Rush had delivered aH his staves, he was right glad in his heart, for he knew right well there should be a great fray among them, either one time or other. So it fortuned afterward, as it is a common cus-tome among religious people at an high feast, to keepe solemne service, and every man to be at Mattens at midnight, and so upon a good night, all the whole Covent assembled together in the Quier, and were ready to begin Mattens, they taried for nothing but for the comming of the Priour. Then anon the Priour came into the Quier, and sate him downe in his place, and as he looked about him, he espied that the Subpriour was there present, and with that his heart began to grudge of the olde anger that was fallen betweene them two, and he thought in his minde that he could never be revenged in a better time, and sodainly he rose out of his place, and went to the Subpriour, and with his fist he gave him a good buffet, and the Subpriour which was moved with the stroke, started unto the Priour and gave him another buffet, and with that they went freshly together by the eares, and when the other Friers saw that, every man rose out of their places, and drew out their Truncheons, and together they went who VOL. I.

prediction.sentence: Their malicious minds and angry hearts led every man to privately approach Frier Rush and borrow staves from him. This resulted in every Frier in the vicinity having one, and they would not leave without their staves concealed under their habits. Each individual kept the possession of their stave a secret from the others.
prediction.region:
Of Friar Rush. 273

Filling their malicious minds and angry hearts, every man went privately to Friar Rush to borrow staves. So much so, that there was not a friar in the place who did not have one. They kept their staves hidden under their habits, and did not know who else had one. When Friar Rush had given away all his staves, he was happy because he knew there would be a big fight among the friars soon.

Afterwards, the friars gathered together for a solemn service at midnight. They waited for the Prior to arrive before they began. When the Prior came into the choir, he saw the Subprior and thought of their old anger between them. He decided to take revenge, and suddenly hit the Subprior with his fist. The Subprior responded by hitting the Prior back. They started fighting, and the other friars joined in with their truncheons.

ocr.region: OF FRYER BACON. 243 George, who fought with the dragon, and killed it Vandermast following his example raysed up Perseus, who fought also with his sea-monster, and kdled it, so were they both released from their danger. They being not contented with this tryall of their skill, went further in their coniurations, and raised up two spirits, each of them one. Bungye charged his spirit for to assist him with the greatest power hee had, that by it he might be able to overcome Vandermast. The Devdl told him he would, if that he from his left arme would give him but three drops of blood but if that he did deny him that, then should Vandermast have power over him to doe what he would the Hke told Vandermasts Devill to him to this demand of the spirits, they both agreed, thinking for to overcome each other but the Devill overthrew them both. They having given the Devill this bloud, as is before spoken of, they both fell againe to their coniurations first, Bungye did rayse Achilles with bis Greekes, who marched about Vandermast and threatned him. Then Vandermast raised Hector with his Troians, who defended him from AchiUes and the Greekes. Then began there a great batteU between the Greekes and Troians, which continued a good space at last Hector was slaine, and the Troians fled. Then did follow a great tempest, with thundring and lightning, so that the two coniurers wished that they had been away. But wishes were in vaine for now the time was come, that the Devill would be paid for the knowledge that he had

And these be the names of the devils. Belphegor who was Prince of Gluttony, Asmodeus Prince of Lechery, and Belzebub Prince of Envie, with many other divels assembled together, which reioyced for the misorder of these religious men. And as they were all assembled together with one accord they chose a divell to goe and dwell among these religious men, for to maintaine them the longer in their ungracious living, which divell was put in rayment Hke an earthly crea ture, and went to a religious house, and there he stood at the gate a certaine space all alone with an heavie countenance. Then within a while after the Priour came unto the gate and espied Rush the young man standing there ad alone. Anon he said unto him, what dost thou here, and what wouldest thou have. The young man with great reverence answered and said Sir, I am a poore young man, and am out of service, and faine would have a maister. And when the great prince of devils which are the patrones of all vices understood of the great misrule and vile living of these religious men consulted to keepe them still in that state, and worse if it might be. And these be the names of the devils. Belphegor who was Prince of Gluttony, Asmodeus Prince of Lechery, and Belzebub Prince of Envie, with many other divels assembled together, which reioyced for the misorder of these religious men. And as they were all assembled together with one accord they chose a divell to goe and dwell among these religious men, for to maintaine them the longer in their ungracious living, which divell was put in rayment like an earthly crea-ture, and went to a religious house, and there he stood at the gate a certaine space all alone with an heavie countenance. Then within a while after the Priour came unto the gate and espied Rush the young man standing there all alone. Anon he said unto him, what dost thou here, and what wouldest thou have. The young man with great reverence answered and said Sir, I am a poore young man, and am out of service, and faine would have a maister. And sir if it please you to have me, I shall doe you diligent service, and shalldoe so well that you and all your brethren and covent shall be glad of me, for I shall keepe so well your secrets, that I trust to obtaine at all times your good love and favour, and all theirs also. And when the Priour had heard his words, he was
